## Detecting and Managing Themes in .NET MAUI

### Get the Current System Theme

```csharp
AppTheme currentTheme = Application.Current.RequestedTheme;
// Returns AppTheme.Light, AppTheme.Dark, or AppTheme.Unspecified
```

### Subscribe to Theme Changes

```csharp
Application.Current.RequestedThemeChanged += (sender, args) =>
{
    AppTheme newTheme = args.RequestedTheme;
    Debug.WriteLine($"Theme changed to: {newTheme}");
    // Update UI or trigger re-theming logic here
};
```

### Force a Specific Theme (Override System Setting)

```csharp
// Force dark mode regardless of system setting
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark;

// Force light mode
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Light;

// Revert to following the system setting
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Unspecified;
```

### Putting It Together

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();

        RequestedThemeChanged += OnThemeChanged;
    }

    private void OnThemeChanged(object sender, AppThemeChangedEventArgs e)
    {
        Debug.WriteLine($"System theme changed to: {e.RequestedTheme}");
        // React to the change — update resources, notify ViewModels, etc.
    }

    public void SetThemeOverride(AppTheme theme)
    {
        UserAppTheme = theme; // Dark, Light, or Unspecified to follow system
    }
}
```

### XAML: Respond Automatically with `AppThemeBinding`

```xml
<Label Text="Hello"
       TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=Black, Dark=White}" />
```

Resources defined with `AppThemeBinding` update automatically when the theme changes — no manual refresh needed.

**Key points:**
- `RequestedTheme` = what the OS reports
- `UserAppTheme` = your app-level override (`Unspecified` means "follow system")
- `RequestedThemeChanged` fires on OS-level changes even if `UserAppTheme` is set (but UI follows the override)
